Skip the flashmla_ops target in sgl-kernel for DGX Spark GB10.

Problem:
  sgl-kernel/CMakeLists.txt includes `cmake/flashmla.cmake` which
  declares a separate `flashmla_ops` Python extension module built from
  sgl-project/FlashMLA — NVIDIA's Multi-Latent-Attention kernel library
  (originally from DeepSeek-AI, forked into the sglang org). The target
  has roughly 25 translation units split across:

    csrc/sm90/decode/{dense,sparse_fp8}/instantiations/*.cu
    csrc/sm90/prefill/sparse/instantiations/*.cu
    csrc/sm100/prefill/{dense,sparse}/*.cu
    csrc/sm100/decode/head{64,128}/instantiations/*.cu
    csrc/extension/sm90/dense_fp8/*.cu

  EVERY source file is either sm_90a (Hopper H100/H200) or sm_100a
  (Blackwell B200). There is no sm_121a dispatch path in FlashMLA at
  all — verified against the sglang v0.5.10 flashmla.cmake source file,
  which only APPENDs `-gencode=arch=compute_90a,code=sm_90a` and
  `-gencode=arch=compute_100a,code=sm_100a` to the FLASHMLA_CUDA_FLAGS.

  On GB10 (compute capability 12.1) neither of these binary variants
  is selected by the CUDA loader, and FlashMLA has no cooperative
  fallback. The entire `flashmla_ops` Python extension builds to
  binary that cannot be loaded on this fleet → pure dead code burning
  ~25 TUs of build time and increasing wheel size.

  FlashMLA's primary use case is MLA-style attention (DeepSeek, Kimi
  K2, etc.) on Hopper/B200. Our target models — Qwen3-235B-A22B-NVFP4,
  Qwen3.5-397B-A17B-NVFP4, GLM-4.7-NVFP4, Gemma4 — all use standard
  attention (MHA/GQA), not MLA, so even if the kernel magically worked
  on GB10 we would not call it.

Fix:
  Wrap the `include(${CMAKE_CURRENT_LIST_DIR}/cmake/flashmla.cmake)`
  call in sgl-kernel/CMakeLists.txt in `if (FALSE) ... endif()`. This
  prevents the cmake file from being loaded at all, so the
  `Python_add_library(flashmla_ops ...)` target, its sources, its
  link/include/install commands, and its cuda flags are never
  processed. Downstream code in CMakeLists.txt does NOT reference the
  `flashmla_ops` target — verified via grep — so skipping the include
  is a clean surgical removal.

  Using if(FALSE) instead of outright deletion preserves the upstream
  structure so future CMake drift is visible in plain diffs; it is
  semantically equivalent to removing the include line.

Runtime safety:
  On GB10 nothing changes. sgl-kernel's Python bindings do not
  unconditionally import `flashmla_ops`; the import is gated by a
  `try/except` similar to the flash_ops/FA3 pattern, and MLA-backed
  models are detected at model-load time. On a fleet that never
  dispatches to MLA attention, the absence of `flashmla_ops` has
  zero observable effect.

  This patch is UNSAFE to apply on a build that will run on Hopper
  GPUs AND serve an MLA-based model (DeepSeek-V2, DeepSeek-V3, Kimi
  K2, etc.). Those need FlashMLA's sm90 kernels. Our fleet neither
  has Hopper silicon nor serves MLA models, so the patch is safe
  here. Do not deploy the resulting wheel to H100/H200 for
  DeepSeek-style MLA inference.

Expected impact:
  - Cuts ~20-25 TUs of sm90/sm100 flashmla compile from the sgl-kernel
    wheel build. On a warm ccache this is a single-digit-minutes save,
    on cold it is more like ~5-10 min.
  - Wheel shrinks by the size of `sgl_kernel/flashmla_ops.*.so` (≥
    100 MiB compiled sm90/sm100 sass).
  - Orthogonal to all four previous cuts (arch-prune, disable-fa3,
    skip-sm90-target, sm121-debug) — stacks cleanly on top of each.

Apply to: sgl-kernel/CMakeLists.txt, inside the Dockerfile builder
stage, BEFORE the sgl-kernel `uv build --wheel` step.

Upstream source: sgl-project/sglang tag v0.5.10.
Context regenerated 2026-06-12 against v0.5.13: the section FOLLOWING the
flashmla include is now "triton kernels" (was "DeepGEMM (JIT)" in v0.5.10)
— the old trailing context only applied via patch's fuzz-2 limit, on
v0.5.12.post1 already. Verified to apply cleanly (no fuzz) on BOTH
v0.5.12.post1 and v0.5.13; the patched region itself is identical in both.

--- a/sgl-kernel/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/sgl-kernel/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -514,7 +514,18 @@
 install(TARGETS spatial_ops LIBRARY DESTINATION sgl_kernel)
 
 # ============================ Extra Install: FLashMLA ============================= #
+# dgxarley sgl-kernel-skip-flashmla.patch: flashmla.cmake builds a separate
+# `flashmla_ops` Python extension from sgl-project/FlashMLA with ~25 TUs
+# targeting sm_90a (Hopper H100) and sm_100a (B200). NONE of these run on
+# GB10 (SM121) — FlashMLA has no sm_121a dispatch path, and the runtime
+# loader would select neither sm90 nor sm100 binaries for compute capability
+# 12.1. The entire flashmla_ops target is dead code on this fleet.
+#
+# Wrapped in `if (FALSE)` instead of removed so upstream drift stays visible
+# in plain diffs; semantically equivalent to deleting the include.
+if (FALSE)
 include(${CMAKE_CURRENT_LIST_DIR}/cmake/flashmla.cmake)
+endif()
 
 # ============================ Extra Install: triton kernels ============================= #
 install(DIRECTORY "${repo-triton_SOURCE_DIR}/python/triton_kernels/triton_kernels/"
